AB Medical sociology ranges from studies of formal medical care to those of
   health, healing, and caring practices outside the health care system
   This field has had a history of ethnographic and qualitative research
   since ifs beginnings. Because few studies in medical sociology derive
   from immersion in a setting, the authors examine those qualitative works
   in which researchers and subjects had sustained contact. They focus only
   on major areas in which ethnographic contributions have clustered: (1)
   disability, chronic illness, and terminal illness; (2) caring and
   curing; (3) medical sociology in aging research; (4) socialization into
   health care professions; and (5) the ethnography of ethics. Throughout
   this review, the added value of ethnographic research to each specific
   area is noted. Ethnographic research has enriched medical sociology with
   its emphasis an descriptive detail, meanings, ongoing processes, and
   concepts. The article ends with a discussion of methodological
   considerations for conducting research and a summary statement.
