   renewable resources from the coastal marsh. Later, by the 1920s, the
   discovery of oil and gas led to the rapid development of an offshore,
   nonrenewable extractive system that is literally unparalleled on the
   planet. In contrast, at the time of early settlement, southern Florida
   had fewer recognized renewable or nonrenewable resources; its
   development began later, centered around amenity use rather than
   consumptive use of resources. In spite of potentially massive economic
