AB There is increasing sociological interest in formal models of action
   driven by a calculus of expected utility. We believe these efforts to
   extend microeconomic models to extraeconomic exchange can benefit from
   specification of societal constraints on individual choice. One type of
   constraint locates the actor in an evolving network of social ties that
   limit opportunities for exchange. Another approach assumes that choices
   are influenced by unintended outcomes that operate behind the backs of
   the actors. Considerable progress has been made in the past two years
