AB One source of sociology's organizational and academic problems is a
   growing lack of intellectual self-definition. The frequent celebration
   of sociology as a multiparadigm discipline is both an effect and a
   source of this lack of self-definition. Some of the roots of the present
   crisis are traced to the acceptance of outside values, ideological and
   otherwise, as a means of specifying what is and is not sociologically
   appropriate. As this occurs, we become more and more an adjunct of other
   intellectual and policy-oriented projects, becoming less and less a
   distinctive and intellectually credible discipline that has much to
   offer on ifs own terms. Not being vital to ourselves, we cease to be
   vital to others.
